{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"669316d7-806c-42a0-9dfd-48c9b457f2dd","content":"I can help guide you on analyzing your .NET crash dump. Here's how:\n\n### Using `dotnet-dump analyze`\n```bash\n# Install the tool if needed\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n\n# Open the dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\n\nOnce inside the interactive session, useful commands:\n\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n| `pe` (or `printexception`) | Print the last exception |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary |\n| `setthread <id>` | Switch threads |\n\n### Typical workflow\n1. Run `pe` to check for an unhandled exception\n2. Run `clrthreads` to find threads with exceptions\n3. Use `setthread` + `clrstack` to inspect each thread's stack\n\n### Alternatives\n- **Visual Studio** — open the `.dmp` file directly for a GUI experience\n- **lldb** with SOS plugin — on Linux/macOS\n- **WinDbg** — on Windows, with the SOS extension (`!analyze -v`)\n\nWould you like me to walk you through running any of these tools on your dump file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0e1cdb43-4dec-4c3e-9d83-4a7e809e890a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description says it's for configuring and collecting crash dumps, and explicitly states \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze, profiling or tracing.\"\n\nSo the dump-collect skill is not appropriate here. I should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing their dump file.","outputTokens":430,"requestId":"6008:15FDF:E23670:1064D2B:69EACC38"},"id":"2a8d0d4f-f2f6-430d-a1e0-ca3d5891279f","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:49:56.079Z","parentId":"008bf469-039d-4aa8-8223-e4db1d624109"}
